Wash and dry all produce @water{and the stock concentrate} to a boil in a small #pot{}. Cut the @corn on the cob{1} of the cob. Core, seed, and finely dice the @red bell pepper{1}. Mince the @jalapeño{1}, removing the ribs and stems if you prefer less heat. Halve the @lime{1}. Roughly chop the @cilantro{1/4%ounce}.

Add the @quinoa{3/4%cup} to the boiling water, cover, and reduce to a low simmer for ~{15-20%minutes}, until tender.

Heat a medium #stainless steel pan{} over medium heat. Add the @pepitas{1%ounce} and cook, tossing for ~{2-3%minutes}, until toasted and fragrant. Remove from the pan and set aside.

Char the corn: Add the corn, @cumin{1%teaspoon}, jalapeño (to taste) and a drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon} to the same pan over medium-high heat. Cook, tossing for ~{4-5%minutes}, until slightly charred. Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Once the quinoa is ready, fluff with a #fork{}. In a large #bowl{}, toss the quinoa with the charred corn, jalapeño, bell pepper, cilantro, a squeeze of lime juice and a drizzle of olive oil. Season generously with salt and pepper. Divide between plates and sprinkle with the pepitas and @feta cheese{1/2%cup}. Enjoy!

> It might seem unconventional to combine so many ingredients, but keep an open mind! The combination of textures and flavors is what makes this "jumble" so great.